    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-06-07T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="88"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d88">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/1136: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-06-07T14:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 7, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 7—6:08 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>151. 1. In my initial interview today with the new Foreign Minister,<note n="22"
                        xml:id="d88fn22">Koki Hirota returned to this post in the Cabinet of Prince
                        Fumimaro Konoye on June 4.</note> Hirota asked me to tell the President and
                    yourself that his <pb facs="0117" n="110" xml:id="pg_110"/> guiding policy in
                    conducting Japan’s relations with the United States would be based on the
                    exchange of messages with you in 1934.<note n="23" xml:id="d88fn23">Exchanged on
                        February 21 and March 3, 1934, <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_127">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 127</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1931-41v01#pg_129">129</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. With regard to the Sino-Japanese affairs he said that his former “three
                    points” were too abstract for present circumstances. He therefore proposed to
                    find concrete solutions of the various outstanding problems between Japan and
                    China.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
